programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.sub-title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: A war that reached every continent and touched every sort of terrain demanded every sort of strategy. In this episode, we examine battles fought at sea, and in the jungle, in city streets, invasions from the air, and retreats from the land.
programme.series-desc: Every battle is both a victory and a defeat; it depends which flag you fly. The battles of World War II were decided not only by strategy but by armies in their element. These battles won and lost would determine the course of the future.

programme.title: Pirates

programme.title: Impossible Peace
programme.desc: In effort to keep peace, treaties were proposed to keep the aggressors of World War 1 under-armed. The ratio of military power was drastically in favor of the US and Great Britain. This might have successfully kept peace, if it was only given a chance.
programme.series-desc: Two world wars tore the heart out of the twentieth century. Between these wars was an age that is viewed as a time of jazz, prohibition, the talkies, radio and the motor car. A time that, in reality, was an age of anxiety. A peace that failed.

programme.title: The First World War
programme.desc: The Turkish Ottoman Empire proved a formidable foe, as Allies found to their cost at Gallipoli and in the Middle East
programme.series-desc: This stunning account of WW1 offers new interpretations of and insights into one of the defining events of the twentieth century. It offers a truly global vision of a war that is so often misconceived as a prolonged skirmish on the Western Front.

programme.title: Guy Martin: Industrial Wonders
programme.desc: Guy's project this week is one of the more surprising legacies of the Victorian period – the public park. Guy is helping with vital renovation work at one of the most significant Victorian parks still open today: Birmingham Botanical Gardens.
programme.series-desc: In this six part series mechanic, motorcycle racer and engineering enthusiast Guy Martin celebrates the workers of Britain's Industrial Revolution by getting stuck into six of the country's biggest restoration project.

programme.title: The Complete Story of Hitler and the Nazis
programme.sub-title: The Complete Hitler and the Nazis
programme.desc: Hitler evolved an entirely new faith, complete with holy book, venerated relics and a priestly elite in the form of Himmler’s SS. Hitler himself was viewed as the ultimate leader in Messianic terms.
programme.series-desc: The murderous deeds of Hitler’s Third Reich are still widely recalled today, but what is less well known is the strange concoction of beliefs that underpinned the Nazi regime.

programme.title: Crimes That Made History
programme.desc: In 1888, a series of gruesome murders shocked London: The perpetrator was dubbed “Jack the Ripper”. This was the Victorian era when puritanism reigned and forensic science was in its infancy.
programme.series-desc: Crimes and bloody tales that made the headlines usually reveal a lot about the hidden fantasies of their time. From Jack the Ripper to the Andes crash, the ten episodes of this collection shed a black light on a page of history that left a mark on time.

programme.title: Dates That Made History
programme.desc: Alexander’s death marks the loss of the greatest conquerors in History, the only man who managed to extend the Empire to Eurasia, the Mediterranean, and India. Different versions of The Romance of Alexander were found in the Persian, Arabian and Latin.
programme.series-desc: This series tells world history through a few major dates, revisited through the prism of memory. Driven by the accessible and passionate delivery of historian Patrick Boucheron, history comes to life under our eyes with bold and entertaining graphics.

programme.title: Big Bad Battles
programme.desc: In 1014, King Brian Boru of Ireland destroyed a Viking army at the Battle of Clontarf. 1000 years later, Barry gathers reenactors from all over the world to restage this famous battle.
programme.series-desc: Have you ever wondered what life was like for Vikings or WWII “squaddies?” Alex Jordan follows a group of weekend battle reenactors in this glorious celebration of British eccentricity.

programme.title: Gallipoli
programme.desc: In August, to break the stalemate at Gallipoli, General Hamilton coordinates a complicated series of feints and attacks against the Turks.
programme.series-desc: As dawn breaks on the 25th April, 1915, Anzac troops go into battle on the beaches of the Gallipoli peninsula in Turkey.

programme.title: Navy SEALs: Untold Stories
programme.desc: SEAL Team 6 sneaks into Bosnia packed inside metal cargo containers to capture a brutal Serbian politician indicted for crimes against humanity.
programme.series-desc: Based on first-person accounts, the U.S. Navy SEALs face battle savagely but in secret. This extraordinary mini-series includes seven actual, classified missions - from planning through preparation to heart-stopping execution.

programme.title: Sea Power
programme.desc: The civilizations that grew up around the Mediterranean were the most important of their age. From Egypt to Rome, it was Mediterranean nations who led the Western world with warfare.
programme.series-desc: This documentary series dives deep into the development and creation of the world's most important nautical warships.

programme.title: Under Siege
programme.desc: Here at Ciudad Rodrigo, there was the bloody business of siege warfare – where civilians and soldiers share the same conditions and privations.
programme.series-desc: This docu-miniseries explores siege warfare and explains how those that are vastly outnumbered have stood behind walls and barricades in a last stand against their attackers.

programme.title: The First World War
programme.desc: As the Germans and Austrians clashed with the Russians on the bitter Eastern Front, Italy became embroiled in a terrible slaughter, where people fought in the worst of terrains under harsh conditions
programme.series-desc: This stunning account of WW1 offers new interpretations of and insights into one of the defining events of the twentieth century. It offers a truly global vision of a war that is so often misconceived as a prolonged skirmish on the Western Front.

programme.title: Weapons Race
programme.desc: As soon as the idea of strategic bombing was conceived, men began to look at ways of detecting them – or at evading this detection.
programme.series-desc: Examine the development of new military technologies and how their evolution impacted tactics and strategies used in warfare from the High Middle Ages to the Modern Era.

programme.title: Battleplan
programme.desc: Counterstrike can take many forms and history is full of examples where a numerically inferior army has turned the tide of battle by a brilliant execution of a Counterstrike. Discover three historical examples of successful counterstrike’s.
programme.series-desc: Examine the history of military tactics, from blitzkrieg to blockade, raiding operations to strategic bombing and on to guerrilla warfare.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.sub-title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Some words transcend their origins as humble place names. They are carved into history as turning points which influenced the course of WWII, the fate of nations, and the make-up of our world. El Alamein, Okinawa, and Pearl Harbor.
programme.series-desc: Every battle is both a victory and a defeat; it depends which flag you fly. The battles of World War II were decided not only by strategy but by armies in their element. These battles won and lost would determine the course of the future.
